      {
        "id": 2955099,
        "name": "Tegan Passalacqua",
        "username": "Tegan_Passalacqua",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/838e76/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2020-08-12T00:14:32.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"163202\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>There is a decent about written on the history of winemaking and grape-growing in the Napa Valley, both before prohibition and during the boom in the late 60s / early 70s.  Is there anything worth reading on the history of Sonoma? Doesn\u2019t have to be a book: a history of a vineyard would also be interesting.  I love reading about sites that still have old-vine material on them today, or have been continuously farmed, but there just isn\u2019t much that I\u2019ve seen about Sonoma.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>History of the Sonoma Viticultural district by Ernest Peninou would be your best bet and my favorite. When you want to get really geeky and finish the first recommendation, Legacy of a village- The Italian Swiss Colony Winery and People of Asti, California would be a great follow up.<br>\nBest,<br>\nTegan</p>",
